  <!-- 03 Findings -->
  <article class="chapter">
    <div class="chapter-num mono">
      <span>CHAPTER</span>
      <span class="big">03</span>
    </div>
    <div>
      <div class="kicker mono">WHAT IT CHECKS</div>
      <h2>Five signal classes, every finding explained.</h2>
      <p class="lede">Every check produces the same shape of result — a severity, a short technical reason, and a concrete remediation. The risk score is the rolled-up view; the per-finding output is what an engineer actually fixes from.</p>

      <div class="findings">
        <div class="finding">
          <div class="idx mono">C.01 · ASSET DISCOVERY</div>
          <h3>Subdomains via Certificate Transparency.</h3>
          <p>Passive enumeration over public CT logs. Deterministic — no wordlists, no brute force. Degrades gracefully when corporate proxies block the lookup.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="finding">
          <div class="idx mono">C.02 · TRANSPORT SECURITY</div>
          <h3>TLS protocol versions and certificate expiry.</h3>
          <p>Detects deprecated TLS 1.0 / 1.1 endpoints and certificates approaching expiry. Both are silent failures until the day they aren't.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="finding">
          <div class="idx mono">C.03 · HTTP HEADERS</div>
          <h3>HSTS, CSP, X-Frame-Options, X-Content-Type-Options, Referrer-Policy.</h3>
          <p>The header set the OWASP Secure Headers Project treats as table stakes. Each missing or weak value produces an explicit finding with a fix.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="finding">
          <div class="idx mono">C.04 · RISK SCORING</div>
          <h3>Asset-level risk, scan-level summary, top contributors.</h3>
          <p>Rules-based, explainable, reproducible. The summary names the top reasons the score is what it is — no opaque number to argue with.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="finding">
          <div class="idx mono">C.05 · ENTERPRISE FALLBACK</div>
          <h3>Proxy-aware degradation.</h3>
          <p>In restricted networks where CT lookups or HTTPS probes fail, the scanner emits structured warnings instead of crashing. The report says exactly what was skipped and why.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

  <!-- 04 Out of scope -->
  <article class="chapter">
    <div class="chapter-num mono">
      <span>CHAPTER</span>
      <span class="big">04</span>
    </div>
    <div>
      <div class="kicker mono">OUT OF SCOPE</div>
      <h2>What the tool intentionally does not do.</h2>
      <div class="body">
        <p>No exploitation. No authenticated crawling. No port scanning beyond the standard HTTP/HTTPS probe. No vulnerability scanning. No brute forcing. No intrusive traffic generation. No credentials, secrets, or sensitive data are collected.</p>
        <p>The boundary is the entire point. A scanner that stays inside this boundary is safe to run against production-like environments, safe to wire into CI for drift detection, and safe to point at a partner's domain during a procurement review without writing a memo first.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="code-head mono">scanner · usage · simplified</div>
      <pre class="code"><span class="c"># single command, single domain</span>
$ python -m ass.cli example.com

<span class="c"># produces:</span>
results/scan_&lt;timestamp&gt;.json   <span class="c"># structured artifact</span>
                                <span class="c"># + rich CLI summary:</span>
                                <span class="c">#   risk overview</span>
                                <span class="c">#   top risky assets</span>
                                <span class="c">#   finding counts</span>
                                <span class="c">#   environment warnings</span></pre>
    </div>
  </article>

  <!-- 05 Engineering -->
  <article class="chapter">
    <div class="chapter-num mono">
      <span>CHAPTER</span>
      <span class="big">05</span>
    </div>
    <div>
      <div class="kicker mono">ENGINEERING</div>
      <h2>Boring on purpose.</h2>
      <div class="body">
        <p>Clean <span class="mono">src/</span>-layout Python package. Pydantic models for typed data flow. Deterministic scoring logic with unit-test coverage. <span class="mono">ruff</span> for static analysis, <span class="mono">pytest</span> matrix across Python 3.10 / 3.11 / 3.12, GitHub Actions CI on every push. Nothing exotic — the kind of engineering hygiene a security tool earns its trust from.</p>
        <p>Roadmap is incremental: baseline comparison and drift detection across runs, extended TLS analysis (cipher suites, curves), JSON schema versioning so downstream consumers stay stable, and a containerised read-only execution mode for cloud runners.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="repo-card mono">
        <div class="k">REPOSITORY</div>
        <a href="https://github.com/richter-max/attack-surface-scanner" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">github.com/richter-max/attack-surface-scanner →</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

